User Story
As a prospective candidate, I want my selected client market to map to an appropriate
historical income range so that the estimate reflects the type of market I intend to serve.
Description
This story covers the business logic that translates the candidate’s Market Served
selection into an income range. The BRD defines four market segments: Mass Market, Mid
Market, Affluent, and High Net Worth. These segments are mapped to historical FYC ranges
using the  first-year prior agent income distribution after filtering out the top and
bottom % of agents by FYC.[]
The  FYC distribution is divided into ten deciles. Each market segment spans multiple
deciles, and adjacent segments intentionally overlap. This overlap reflects the practical
reality that candidates serving adjacent markets may have similar outcomes at the edges of
the distribution.
Segment Mapping Requirements
The High Net Worth segment requires special handling. The BRD indicates that High Net
Worth is anchored at Decile  rather than a strict fourth quartile because agents serving
high-net-worth markets write larger cases by nature. The range ceiling is the actual th
percentile of the  data, shown as approximately $,.[]
